  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Junctions are where the action is, and sometimes, the cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, junctional nevus. This type of nevus is considered to have the highest malignant potential because its melanocytes are located at the dermal-epidermal junction, a critical interface for cellular activity and potential transformation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nJunctional nevi are characterized by nests of melanocytes located at the interface between the epidermis and the dermis. This location is significant because it is where melanocytes are most actively proliferating and interacting with keratinocytes and the basement membrane. The constant cellular turnover and exposure to environmental factors at this junction increase the likelihood of genetic mutations and dysplastic changes, which can predispose to malignant transformation into melanoma. Their flat or slightly raised appearance, often with uniform pigmentation, can sometimes mask early atypical features.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Intradermal nevi have melanocytes located entirely within the dermis. These nevi are typically mature, stable, and have very low malignant potential, often appearing as dome-shaped, flesh-colored papules.\nOption C (Incorrect): Blue nevi are characterized by deep dermal melanocytes that produce melanin, giving them a blue or blue-black appearance due to the Tyndall effect. While some rare variants exist, the vast majority of blue nevi are benign and have minimal malignant potential compared to junctional nevi.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Junctional Nevus | Intradermal Nevus | Blue Nevus |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location of Melanocytes** | Dermal-epidermal junction | Entirely within dermis | Deep dermis |\n| **Malignant Potential** | Highest | Very Low | Very Low (rare exceptions) |\n| **Typical Appearance** | Flat, macule, uniform brown/black | Dome-shaped, flesh-colored/tan papule | Blue/blue-black papule/nodule |\n| **Progression** | Can progress to compound nevus or melanoma | Stable, mature | Stable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Junctional nevi are at the junction of danger for melanoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, a junctional nevus appears as a flat or slightly raised macule or papule, typically uniformly pigmented brown or black. Dermoscopy may reveal a reticular pattern or homogeneous globular pattern.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Melanoma (2023). Recommends regular skin exams and biopsy for suspicious lesions, especially those with atypical features or changes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | junctional nevus | ✅ Correct |\n| B | intradermal nevus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | blue nevus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
