  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Melanoma margins: Breslow is boss!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 2 cm. For a melanoma with a Breslow thickness of 3 mm, current surgical guidelines recommend a 2 cm wide local excision margin to achieve adequate local control while minimizing morbidity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWide local excision is the primary treatment for localized melanoma, and the appropriate margin is critical for preventing local recurrence. The Breslow thickness, which is the depth of invasion from the granular layer of the epidermis to the deepest tumor cell, is the most important prognostic factor and dictates the recommended excision margin. For melanomas measuring between 2.01 mm and 4.0 mm in thickness, a 2 cm margin has been shown to provide equivalent oncologic outcomes to wider excisions with less tissue removal and reconstructive complexity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (1 cm): Incorrect. A 1 cm margin is typically recommended for thinner melanomas, specifically those with a Breslow thickness between 0.76 mm and 2.0 mm.\nOption C (3 cm): Incorrect. While historically larger margins were sometimes used, current evidence-based guidelines do not support a 3 cm margin for a 3 mm thick melanoma, as 2 cm provides equivalent local control.\nOption D (4 cm): Incorrect. This margin is excessively wide for a 3 mm melanoma and would lead to unnecessary tissue defects and reconstructive challenges without offering additional survival benefit.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Breslow Thickness | Recommended Excision Margin |\n|---|---|\n| In situ melanoma | 0.5 - 1 cm |\n| < 1.0 mm | 1 cm |\n| 1.01 - 2.0 mm | 1 - 2 cm (often 1 cm is sufficient) |\n| 2.01 - 4.0 mm | 2 cm |\n| > 4.0 mm | 2 cm (or individualized) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Breslow thickness dictates melanoma excision margins.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring wide local excision, the surgeon meticulously marks the planned margin based on the preoperative Breslow thickness, ensuring adequate tissue removal. Intraoperatively, the goal is to achieve clear margins, which are then confirmed by permanent pathology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Melanoma (e.g., 2023). The NCCN Guidelines recommend a 2 cm surgical excision margin for primary cutaneous melanoma with a Breslow thickness between 2.01 mm and 4.0 mm.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 2 cm | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 3 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 4 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
