  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Numb ear after parotidectomy? Blame the great auricular nerve!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, the great auricular nerve. This nerve is the most commonly injured nerve during parotid surgery due to its superficial course and proximity to the surgical field during skin flap elevation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe great auricular nerve originates from the cervical plexus (C2-C3) and ascends superficially over the sternocleidomastoid muscle, providing sensory innervation to the skin overlying the parotid gland, mastoid process, and lower ear. During parotidectomy, particularly with standard incisions, the nerve is directly in the path of dissection when raising skin flaps. Its vulnerable superficial location makes it highly susceptible to traction or transection injury, leading to a common post-operative complaint of numbness in its sensory distribution.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Facial nerve injury is a feared and significant complication due to its motor function, but it is less common than great auricular nerve injury because meticulous dissection techniques are employed to identify and preserve it.\nOption C (Incorrect): The auriculotemporal nerve provides sensation to the temple and parotid capsule and carries parasympathetic fibers. While it can be injured, leading to Frey's syndrome or temporal numbness, it is less frequently affected than the great auricular nerve.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Function | Common Injury in Parotidectomy | Clinical Manifestation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Great Auricular Nerve | C2-C3 (cervical plexus) | Sensation to parotid, mastoid, lower ear | Most common (transection/traction) | Numbness/anesthesia in distribution |\n| Facial Nerve | Cranial Nerve VII | Motor to muscles of facial expression | Feared (transection/traction/thermal) | Facial weakness/paralysis |\n| Auriculotemporal Nerve | V3 (trigeminal nerve) | Sensation to temple/parotid, parasympathetic to parotid | Less common (traction/thermal) | Frey's syndrome, temporal numbness |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Superficial great auricular nerve is the most common parotidectomy casualty.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, the great auricular nerve is typically identified crossing the sternocleidomastoid muscle obliquely, approximately 6.5 cm inferior to the external auditory canal, during the initial skin flap elevation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Parotidectomy (2016). Recommends careful identification and preservation of the facial nerve and its branches, implicitly highlighting the need for awareness of all surrounding neurovascular structures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Facial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | great auricular nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Auricular temporal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
