  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's bloody from the nipple, a papilloma is the culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Intraductal papilloma is indeed the most common cause of spontaneous, unilateral, bloody nipple discharge, particularly in premenopausal women, due to its friable nature within the breast ducts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas are benign epithelial proliferations that grow within the lactiferous ducts. Their delicate, vascularized fronds are prone to microtrauma from normal breast movements or pressure, leading to rupture of small capillaries and subsequent bloody discharge from the nipple. This discharge is typically unilateral and from a single duct orifice.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Duct ectasia) (Incorrect): Duct ectasia typically presents with a thick, sticky, multi-colored (often green, black, or brown) discharge, and is less commonly associated with frank bloody discharge. It's due to dilation of the subareolar ducts.\nOption C (Duct hyperplasia) (Incorrect): Duct hyperplasia, while a proliferative lesion, is generally asymptomatic or may present as a mass. It is not a common cause of nipple discharge, and certainly not typically bloody discharge.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Discharge | Malignancy Risk | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Intraductal Papilloma | Bloody, unilateral, spontaneous | Low (benign) | Friable lesion within duct |\n| Duct Ectasia | Multi-colored (green/black/brown), sticky | None (benign) | Dilated subareolar ducts |\n| Duct Hyperplasia | Usually none | Varies (mild to atypical) | Epithelial proliferation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody nipple discharge = think papilloma first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, an intraductal papilloma may appear as a solid mass within a dilated duct. A ductogram (galactogram) can visualize the filling defect caused by the papilloma within the duct system. Surgical excision reveals a small, frond-like lesion within the duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on Nipple Discharge (2019): Recommends evaluation for pathologic nipple discharge, with intraductal papilloma being a common benign cause.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | intraductal paplioma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Duct ectasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Duct hyperplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
