  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 One bad gland? Just take that one!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Targeted parathyroidectomy is the correct next step for primary hyperparathyroidism with elevated calcium and PTH, as it is the standard, minimally invasive approach when localization studies suggest a single adenoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary hyperparathyroidism is most commonly caused by a single parathyroid adenoma (80-85%). Targeted parathyroidectomy, guided by pre-operative localization studies like Sestamibi scan and ultrasound, allows for removal of only the affected gland. This minimally invasive approach leads to lower complication rates, faster recovery, and excellent cure rates while preserving normal parathyroid tissue to prevent permanent hypoparathyroidism.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Total parathyroidectomy is generally reserved for specific situations such as multigland hyperplasia (e.g., in MEN syndromes), parathyroid carcinoma, or re-operations where previous targeted surgery failed. It carries a significantly higher risk of permanent hypoparathyroidism, which is a major morbidity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Targeted Parathyroidectomy | Total Parathyroidectomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Indication | Single adenoma (80-85% of PHPT) | Multigland hyperplasia, carcinoma, failed prior surgery |\n| Approach | Minimally invasive, focused | More extensive neck exploration |\n| Complications | Lower risk of permanent hypoparathyroidism | Higher risk of permanent hypoparathyroidism |\n| Pre-op Localization | Essential for success | Less critical, but still helpful |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Localize the adenoma, then target it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPre-operative imaging with Technetium-99m Sestamibi scan and neck ultrasound is crucial to localize the hyperfunctioning parathyroid gland. Intraoperatively, the surgeon identifies the enlarged, often darker, adenomatous gland and confirms removal with intraoperative PTH monitoring.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Primary Hyperparathyroidism (2016). Recommends targeted parathyroidectomy for patients with primary hyperparathyroidism and concordant localization studies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Total parathyrodectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Targeted parathyrodectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
