  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Diarrhea: Ileitis's tell, appendicitis's rare spell.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 'presence of diarrhea'. This answer correctly identifies a key differentiating symptom between ileitis and acute appendicitis, which is crucial for initial clinical assessment and diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute appendicitis typically presents with anorexia, periumbilical pain migrating to the right lower quadrant, nausea, and vomiting. Diarrhea is uncommon in classic appendicitis and, if present, might suggest an atypical presentation or an alternative diagnosis. In contrast, ileitis, which is inflammation of the terminal ileum, frequently presents with right lower quadrant pain accompanied by diarrhea, often due to the inflammatory process affecting small bowel absorption and motility. This symptomatic difference is a fundamental clinical discriminator.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The time course between acute and subacute symptoms can be variable for both conditions and is not a reliable or specific differentiating factor. Both ileitis and appendicitis can have a relatively rapid onset and progression.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Acute Appendicitis                               | Ileitis (e.g., Crohn's, infectious)             |\n|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|\n| **Pain Location**   | Periumbilical migrating to RLQ                   | RLQ, often more diffuse                         |\n| **Anorexia**        | Common                                           | Variable, often present                         |\n| **Nausea/Vomiting** | Common                                           | Variable, often present                         |\n| **Diarrhea**        | Uncommon, suggests atypical or alternative dx    | Common, often prominent                         |\n| **Fever**           | Common                                           | Common                                          |\n| **Leukocytosis**    | Common                                           | Common                                          |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Diarrhea in RLQ pain points away from classic appendicitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, acute appendicitis typically shows a dilated, non-compressible appendix (>6mm diameter), wall thickening, periappendiceal fat stranding, and possibly an appendicolith. For ileitis, CT imaging would reveal thickening of the terminal ileum wall, mesenteric fat stranding, and potentially enlarged regional lymph nodes, without specific appendiceal findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020). These guidelines emphasize clinical assessment and imaging for diagnosis, noting atypical presentations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the time between the acute and subacute symptoms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | presence of diarrhea | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
