  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 BRCA risks are specific; know your numbers for targeted care!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct because BRCA1 mutation carriers face a substantial lifetime risk of developing ovarian cancer, with 40% falling within the established range. Understanding these specific genetic risks is crucial for appropriate patient counseling and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBRCA1 and BRCA2 are tumor suppressor genes involved in DNA repair. Mutations in these genes impair their function, leading to an increased risk of various cancers. For BRCA1 carriers, the lifetime risk of ovarian cancer is typically cited as 35-46%, making the 40% figure in option A accurate. This high penetrance necessitates proactive screening and risk-reduction strategies, such as prophylactic oophorectomy, to significantly reduce mortality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While BRCA1 mutations can confer a small increased risk of male breast cancer, BRCA2 mutations are much more strongly associated with male breast cancer, accounting for a higher proportion of cases.\nOption C (Incorrect): BRCA1 mutations, along with BRCA2, are responsible for approximately 5-10% of all breast cancers, not 90%. The vast majority of breast cancers are sporadic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gene | Lifetime Breast Cancer Risk | Lifetime Ovarian Cancer Risk | Male Breast Cancer Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| BRCA1 | 45-85% | 35-46% | Low (1-5%) |\n| BRCA2 | 45-85% | 11-27% | Higher (5-10%) |\n| General Population | ~12% | ~1-2% | <0.1% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: BRCA1 for ovarian cancer, BRCA2 for male breast cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to genetic risk assessment and does not directly involve imaging or intraoperative findings. No specific imaging or intraoperative pearl is applicable here.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Genetic/Familial High-Risk Assessment: Breast, Ovarian, and Pancreatic (2024) recommend genetic testing for individuals meeting specific criteria and outline management strategies based on mutation status.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Patient with BRAC 1 has 40% risk to developing ovarian cancer ** | ✅ Correct |\n| B | BRAC 1 associated with male breast ca | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | BRAC 1 mutation associated with 90% of breast ca | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) BRCA 2 is associated with male breast cancer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
