  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Insulinomas: small, hypervascular, and found everywhere in the pancreas.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer states that insulinomas are evenly distributed along the pancreas. This is a crucial characteristic for these neuroendocrine tumors, distinguishing them from other pancreatic pathologies that often have a predilection for specific regions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInsulinomas are typically small, solitary, and benign neuroendocrine tumors arising from the beta cells of the pancreatic islets. Unlike pancreatic adenocarcinomas, which predominantly occur in the head of the pancreas, insulinomas do not exhibit a preferential location. They are found with roughly equal frequency in the head, body, and tail of the pancreas, making a thorough and systematic exploration of the entire gland essential during surgical localization and resection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (90% in the head) (Incorrect): This distribution is characteristic of pancreatic adenocarcinoma, not insulinoma.\nOption C (10% in the tail) (Incorrect): While some insulinomas are found in the tail, this percentage does not accurately represent their overall distribution, which is even across the entire organ.\nOption D (50 % in the body) (Incorrect): There is no specific predilection for the body of the pancreas; insulinomas are evenly distributed.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Typical Location |\n|---|---|\n| Insulinoma | Evenly distributed throughout the pancreas |\n| Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma | Predominantly head (60-70%) |\n| Gastrinoma | Gastrinoma triangle (Passaro's triangle: junction of cystic duct and common bile duct, second and third portions of duodenum, head of pancreas) |\n| VIPoma | Often in the tail of the pancreas (75%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Insulinomas are pan-pancreatic; they don't favor any specific region.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT, MRI, EUS), insulinomas typically appear as small (<2 cm), hypervascular lesions. Intraoperatively, they are often solitary, well-circumscribed, and can be difficult to palpate, necessitating intraoperative ultrasound for precise localization throughout the entire pancreas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNorth American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Tumors (2010, updated periodically) recommend comprehensive imaging and surgical exploration given their diffuse distribution.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 90% in the head | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | evenly distributed along the pancreas | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 10% in the tail | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 50 % in the body | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
