  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FTSG: Less shrink, more sink.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, \"Less contracture.\" Full-thickness skin grafts (FTSGs) are advantageous over split-thickness skin grafts (STSGs) primarily because they contain the entire dermal layer, which significantly reduces post-graft contraction, leading to better functional and cosmetic outcomes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFull-thickness skin grafts include the entire epidermis and dermis, providing a more robust and stable graft. The presence of a complete dermal layer, rich in collagen and elastic fibers, along with adnexal structures like hair follicles and sweat glands, acts as a scaffold that resists both primary and secondary wound contraction. This inherent structural integrity minimizes distortion of surrounding tissues and provides a more natural appearance and texture, making FTSGs ideal for areas requiring minimal contracture, such as the face, hands, or over joints.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): FTSGs are limited by donor site availability and typically cover smaller defects compared to STSGs, which can cover larger surface areas.\nOption B (Incorrect): The risk of infection is generally similar for both graft types, though FTSGs require a more robust vascular bed for survival, and compromise can lead to graft loss.\nOption C (Incorrect): While FTSGs generally provide a better color and texture match than STSGs, \"less contracture\" is a more distinct and functionally significant advantage that often dictates their use over STSGs.\nOption D (Incorrect): FTSGs are more metabolically demanding and thus more dependent on a robust blood supply from the recipient bed for survival due to their increased thickness, making them more susceptible to failure with poor vascularity, not less.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Full-Thickness Skin Graft (FTSG) | Split-Thickness Skin Graft (STSG) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Thickness** | Epidermis + entire dermis | Epidermis + partial dermis |\n| **Contracture** | Less | More |\n| **Donor Site** | Requires primary closure or grafting | Heals by re-epithelialization |\n| **Survival** | More demanding (requires good blood supply) | Less demanding |\n| **Cosmesis** | Better color/texture match, less contraction | Poorer color/texture match, more contraction |\n| **Coverage** | Smaller defects | Larger defects |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FTSG: Full thickness, full resistance to contracture.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, an FTSG appears thicker and more opaque than an STSG. Its donor site requires primary closure or another graft, unlike an STSG donor site which re-epithelializes spontaneously.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nPrinciples of Reconstructive Surgery (e.g., American College of Surgeons, 2020) emphasize selecting graft type based on wound characteristics and functional/cosmetic goals, with FTSGs preferred for areas where contracture must be minimized.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | larger surface | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | less infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | superficial skin matches | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | less blood supply | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Less contracture | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
