  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Chronic burns can turn bad, think Marjolin's.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Marjolin's ulcer is a rare but aggressive malignancy, most commonly squamous cell carcinoma, that arises in chronic, non-healing wounds or scars. Thermal injury, specifically chronic burn scars, is the most frequent precursor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe underlying mechanism for Marjolin's ulcer involves chronic inflammation and repeated cycles of tissue destruction and repair within a scar. This prolonged irritation, coupled with impaired immune surveillance in devitalized or scarred tissue, creates an environment conducive to malignant transformation. The most common histology is squamous cell carcinoma, but basal cell carcinoma, melanoma, and even sarcoma can occur. The latency period can be decades, emphasizing the importance of long-term surveillance of chronic wounds.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While external irradiation can cause chronic wounds and subsequent malignancy (radiation-induced carcinoma or sarcoma), Marjolin's ulcer specifically refers to malignancy arising in chronic non-healing wounds, with thermal injury being the classic and most common etiology. Radiation-induced cancers are a distinct category.\nOption C (Incorrect): Pressure ulcers (decubitus ulcers) are chronic wounds that can, in rare instances, undergo malignant transformation (Marjolin's ulcer). However, thermal injury (burns) is by far the most common and classic precursor associated with the eponym 'Marjolin's ulcer'.\nOption D (Incorrect): Option B is the correct answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Chronic Wound/Scar | Associated Malignancy (Most Common) | Key Feature/Etiology |\n|:---------------------------|:------------------------------------|:---------------------|\n| Chronic Burn Scar          | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC)       | Marjolin's Ulcer     |\n| Chronic Venous Ulcer       | SCC (rare)                          | Stasis dermatitis    |\n| Chronic Pressure Ulcer     | SCC (rare)                          | Decubitus ulcer      |\n| Irradiated Tissue          | SCC, Sarcoma                        | Radiation exposure   |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Marjolin's ulcer = malignancy in chronic burn scars.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., CT, MRI), Marjolin's ulcer may appear as an irregular, fungating, or indurated mass within a chronic scar, potentially with underlying bone erosion or soft tissue invasion. Intraoperatively, the lesion will be firm, often exophytic or ulcerative, with indurated margins, distinct from the surrounding chronic scar tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Squamous Cell Skin Cancer (2023) recognize chronic inflammation and scarring, including burn scars, as risk factors for SCC, which is the most common malignancy in Marjolin's ulcer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | External irradiation beam | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thermal injury | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Pressure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Non of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) most probably** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
