  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get dislocated by a shoulder dislocation; check the axillary nerve!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Axillary nerve. This nerve is the most frequently injured nerve in anterior shoulder dislocations due to its close anatomical proximity to the surgical neck of the humerus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe axillary nerve (C5, C6) originates from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus. It courses posteriorly, wrapping around the surgical neck of the humerus through the quadrangular space, supplying the deltoid and teres minor muscles, and providing sensory innervation to the skin over the lateral shoulder (regimental badge area). During an anterior dislocation, the humeral head is displaced anteriorly and inferiorly, stretching or compressing the axillary nerve against the glenoid rim or humeral head, leading to neuropraxia or axonotmesis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Median nerve injury is typically associated with supracondylar humeral fractures or carpal tunnel syndrome, not shoulder dislocations.\nOption B (Incorrect): Radial nerve injury is most commonly seen with humeral shaft fractures due to its spiral course around the humerus, not shoulder dislocations.\nOption D (Incorrect): Ulnar nerve injury is often associated with medial epicondyle fractures or cubital tunnel syndrome, not shoulder dislocations.\nOption E (Incorrect): Supraclavicular nerve is a sensory nerve from the cervical plexus, providing sensation to the skin over the clavicle and upper chest, and is not typically injured in shoulder dislocations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Injury Type | Most Common Nerve Injured | Clinical Presentation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anterior Shoulder Dislocation | Axillary Nerve | Deltoid weakness (abduction), sensory loss over \"regimental badge\" area |\n| Humeral Shaft Fracture | Radial Nerve | Wrist drop, sensory loss over dorsal hand/first web space |\n| Supracondylar Humerus Fracture | Median Nerve (anterior interosseous branch) | Loss of pincer grasp (FPL, FDP to index), thenar atrophy |\n| Fibular Head Fracture | Common Peroneal Nerve | Foot drop, sensory loss over dorsum of foot |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anterior shoulder dislocation = Axillary nerve. Think \"A\" for Anterior and Axillary.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, an anterior shoulder dislocation shows the humeral head displaced anteriorly and inferiorly relative to the glenoid. Intraoperatively, one would inspect the axillary nerve for signs of stretching, contusion, or transection, particularly as it courses around the surgical neck.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Shoulder Instability (2019). It recommends thorough neurovascular assessment before and after reduction of shoulder dislocations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Median nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Axillary nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Ulnar nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Supraclavicular nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 486534246-Surgery-ihsan (1).txt**\n",
